h3. Issue Summary

Jira Menu bar icons are too big after upgrade to Jira service desk 4.12 and higher. Same for Jira software 8.12 and higher. There has been fix for the title size in 4.14 version(JRASERVER-71641

) but icons are still big. 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Install Service desk 4.12/Jira software 8.12 or higher
 # Login and verify icons like a cog wheel etc

h3. Expected Results

In the older version these icons were small (cog wheel etc)

!Screenshot 2020-12-16 at 8.34.56 PM.png|width=1067,height=69!
h3. Actual Results

Now the icons are big

!Screenshot 2020-12-16 at 8.32.15 PM.png|width=1060,height=55!
h3. Workaround

[Configure your announcement banner|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/configuring-an-announcement-banner-938846985.html] to include this
{noformat}
<style>
span.aui-icon.aui-icon-small{ --aui-icon-size: 16px; }
.aui-header div.aui-header-before{ margin-right:0; }
span.aui-header-logo-text{ color: #deebff; display: block; float: left; font-size: 14px; margin: 0; padding: 10px 0 10px 10px; }
#header > .aui-header.aui-dropdown2-trigger-group{ border-bottom:none }#announcement-banner {
  padding: 0px !important;
  border-bottom: none !important;
}</style>{noformat}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-2698].
  {panel}



*Original request description:*
 
In my work's instance of JIRA we have multiple products that usually get released as a part of a larger project. It would be a lot nicer if we had a way to edit multiple projects at the same time, mainly to add new versions, release the version.
Would also be nice if JIRA knew those versions were the same, apart from the same name, so a report could be created on it etc.

h3. Summary

Jira installer throws below mentioned error message while trying to drop a column from compressed table.
  
{code:java}
2020-11-16 15:16:13,540+0100 Caesium-1-4 ERROR [c.a.jira.upgrade.UpgradeScheduler] Error occurred during execution of upgrades
com.atlassian.jira.upgrade.UpgradeException
* The upgrade task manager has returned a non-successful result from running the upgrades
Caused by: Error : 1430, Position : 40, Sql = ALTER TABLE CWD_DIRECTORY_ATTRIBUTE ADD ATTRIBUTE_VALUE_TMP CLOB, OriginalSql = ALTER TABLE CWD_DIRECTORY_ATTRIBUTE ADD ATTRIBUTE_VALUE_TMP CLOB, Error Msg = ORA-01430: column being added already exists in table
at oracle.jdbc.driver.T4CTTIoer11.processError(T4CTTIoer11.java:498)
{code}
h3. Environment

Jira Server
h3. Expected Results

The Jira upgrade will complete successfully automatically without manual intervention and installer should handle the compressed table.
h3. Actual Results

Upgrade is failed with error(mentioned above).
h3. Workaround

Table CWD_DIRECTORY_ATTRIBUTE was compressed which caused this exception.

Drop the column manually, rename temp column and then Jira restart. 

Please refer below mentioned queries:-
{code:java}
alter table CWD_DIRECTORY_ATTRIBUTE move nocompress;
{code}
{code:java}
alter table
cwd_directory_attribute
rename column
ATTRIBUTE_VALUE_TMP
TO
ATTRIBUTE_VALUE;{code}
{code:java}
SELECT 'ALTER INDEX ' || INDEX_NAME || ' REBUILD;'
FROM USER_INDEXES
WHERE STATUS = 'UNUSABLE';{code}
 
{code:java}
ALTER TABLE CWD_DIRECTORY_ATTRIBUTE DROP COLUMN ATTRIBUTE_VALUE;
{code}
 
{code:java}
ALTER INDEX PK_CWD_DIRECTORY_ATTRIBUTE REBUILD;
{code}

h3. Issue Summary

Refine report operation when clicked opens the pop up which does not anymore wrap up the status/buttons view. this is now presented in one straight line making it difficult for user to browse to any button that is not pop up view.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a workflow in Jira that has 6-10 statuses.
# Create some issues using that workflow.
# Click on reporting icon for that project on left hand side panel. Browse to Cumulative report. 
# Click on refine report drop down/button.

h3. Expected Results
 !Screenshot 2020-12-03 at 7.53.40 PM-1.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Actual Results
 !JIra_814-1.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround
Use following code in announcement banner:
{code:java}
<style type="text/css">
.js-column-options {
 display: inline-block !important;
}
.aui-buttons {
display: inline-block !important;
}
</style>
{code}

h3. Problem Definition

When creating a webhook, it is possible to use certain variables in the URL. These are currently restricted to:
{code:java}
    ${board.id}
    ${issue.id}
    ${issue.key}
    ${mergedVersion.id}
    ${modifiedUser.key}
    ${modifiedUser.name}
    ${project.id}
    ${project.key}
    ${sprint.id}
    ${version.id}
{code}
 
Source: [Webhooks|https://developer.atlassian.com/server/jira/platform/webhooks/]

However it would also be useful if there could be a variable that indicated the event type, such as issue created, issue edited, issue deleted, etc. In turn it would be helpful in some cases if this could be accessed with a variable name such as
{code:java}
${webhook.event} 
{code}
h3. Suggested Solution

Add
{code:java}
${webhook.event} 
{code}
as a valid variable.
h3. Why this is important

Improves the ability to integrate with other systems and more easily identify/share specific event types with those systems.

When creating or modifying an issue, to assign an Insight object to a custom field you are required to use the key for the object:

 

This results in a pay load such as:

 
{code:json}
{
    'project': {'key': 'TEST'},
    'summary': 'Testing issue creation',
    'description': 'Testing issue creation',
    'issuetype': {'name': 'Task'},
    "customfield_10200": [{"key": "Dev-13"}],
}
{code}
Usually (for me) however, the key is something that is not known without querying the Insight API.

I suggest that the value that it can use be enhanced so that either IQL or other fields can be referenced and result in a match such as:

 
{code:json}
{
    'project': {'key': 'TEST'},
    'summary': 'test with name',
    'description': 'Another one',
    'issuetype': {'name': 'Task'},
    "customfield_10200": [{"iql": "name = 'Some Name' and objectType = 'Devices'"}],
}
{code}
or
{code:json}
{
    'project': {'key': 'TEST'},
    'summary': 'test with name',
    'description': 'Another one',
    'issuetype': {'name': 'Task'},
    "customfield_10200": [{"name": "Some Name"}],
}{code}
At present, using the PIP Jira package (appreciate this isn't managed by Atlassian) requires manual querying of the Insight API prior to creating an issue using the payloads above.

While running the Jira Installer to perform an upgrade, the binary is hanging in step *Extracting files*.

The binary tries to change permissions at /var/atlassian/application-data/jira recursively (even the directory permission are already correct).

Some more details about the issue:
 * The home directory is mounted locally (not using a NFS);
 * There is no symbolic link in the home directory;
 * A recursive chmod command running over /var/atlassian/application-data/jira which sizes ~60GB. The whole process takes more than 2h to finish.
